    "fullText": "When producer David O. Selznick needed to film the burning of Atlanta for Gone with the Wind, he decided to actually set fire to old sets on the Selznick International backlot. The December 1938 blaze was so enormous that residents of nearby Culver City, California called the fire department in a panic, convinced the neighborhood was being consumed. Selznick used the footage as a stand-in for Sherman's March, and the scene remains one of cinema's most iconic moments. Seven Technicolor cameras captured the inferno from different angles because they knew they only had one shot at getting it right. The old sets being burned included walls from King Kong and The Garden of Allah. Clark Gable reportedly watched from the sidelines and was offered the role of Rhett Butler that very night.",
