    "fullText": "Stone Mountain, just east of Atlanta, bears the largest high-relief sculpture on Earth: a 90-by-190-foot carving depicting Jefferson Davis, Robert E. Lee, and Stonewall Jackson on horseback. The project was first conceived in 1916 by the United Daughters of the Confederacy, and original sculptor Gutzon Borglum (yes, the Mount Rushmore guy) began work in 1923. But Borglum got into a vicious feud with the memorial association, destroyed his models, and fled the state. It took until 1972 for the carving to finally be completed by different sculptors using thermo-jet torches. The mountain itself is a single exposed piece of quartz monzonite, one of the largest such formations on the planet. It has been a source of intense controversy for decades, with ongoing debates about its Confederate symbolism.",
