    "fullText": "Standing 56 feet tall atop Red Mountain in Birmingham, Alabama, the Vulcan statue is the largest cast-iron figure ever created. Built for the 1904 World's Fair in St. Louis, the Roman god of the forge was meant to showcase Birmingham's iron industry. From 1946 to 2003, Vulcan held a color-changing neon torch: green meant no traffic fatalities that day, red meant someone had died. Locals called it the 'lollipop' and it became a morbid daily check-in for the city. After a major restoration in 2003, the macabre torch was replaced with a historically accurate spear. The statue had previously suffered the indignity of holding a giant Heinz pickle and a Coca-Cola bottle during various advertising campaigns.",
