    "summary": "Montgomery, Alabama was ground zero for the 1955-56 bus boycott sparked by Rosa Parks. For 381 days, 40,000 Black residents walked, carpooled, and biked instead of riding city buses.",
    "fullText": "On December 1, 1955, Rosa Parks refused to give up her bus seat to a white passenger in Montgomery, Alabama, setting off a 381-day boycott that would reshape American civil rights. An estimated 40,000 Black residents stopped riding city buses, organizing an elaborate carpool system of over 300 vehicles. The boycott was devastating to the bus company since Black riders had made up roughly 75% of its customers. A young pastor named Martin Luther King Jr. emerged as the movement's spokesperson, catapulting him to national prominence at just 26 years old. The boycott ended when the Supreme Court ruled bus segregation unconstitutional in Browder v. Gayle. The actual bus Rosa Parks sat on is now in the Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn, Michigan.",
