    "fullText": "The most famous legend in American music says that young Robert Johnson, a mediocre guitar player, went to a crossroads at midnight and handed his guitar to the Devil, who tuned it and handed it back, granting Johnson otherworldly talent. Johnson then recorded some of the most influential blues songs ever made, including 'Cross Road Blues' and 'Hellhound on My Trail,' before dying mysteriously at age 27 in 1938. The legend has been claimed by at least three different intersections in the Mississippi Delta region, with Clarksdale being the most popular candidate. Johnson's death certificate was not discovered until 1968, and the exact circumstances of his death remain disputed to this day. He recorded only 29 songs in his life, but they influenced everyone from Muddy Waters to the Rolling Stones to Eric Clapton. He was one of the original inductees into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame.",
