    "summary": "Avery Island, Louisiana is not actually an island. It is a giant dome of solid rock salt pushing up through the bayou, and the Tabasco pepper sauce factory has been sitting on top of it since 1868.",
    "fullText": "Avery Island is one of five salt dome islands in coastal Louisiana, formed by a massive underground column of rock salt that pushed upward through the surrounding sediment over millions of years. The salt deposit is estimated to be over 50,000 feet deep -- nearly ten miles straight down. The McIlhenny family has been making Tabasco sauce here since 1868, aging their pepper mash in white oak barrels for up to three years. During the Civil War, the salt mine was so strategically valuable that Union forces specifically targeted it in 1863. Today, Avery Island also contains Jungle Gardens, a 170-acre nature preserve with one of the largest snowy egret rookeries in North America. The mine still operates beneath the factory, and workers extract about 500,000 tons of salt per year from its tunnels.",
