    "summary": "New Orleans can't bury people underground because the water table is so high that coffins literally float back up. So the city built elaborate above-ground tombs, earning its cemeteries the nickname 'Cities of the Dead.'",
    "fullText": "New Orleans sits in a bowl-shaped depression where the water table can be as shallow as one foot below the surface. Early settlers discovered to their horror that buried coffins would pop out of the ground during heavy rains and floods, sometimes floating down the street. The solution was above-ground burial in stone and marble tombs, a practice influenced by French and Spanish colonial traditions. St. Louis Cemetery No. 1, opened in 1789, is the oldest and most famous, containing the alleged tomb of voodoo queen Marie Laveau. The tomb structures function as ovens in the Louisiana heat, essentially cremating remains over time so that multiple family members can be interred in a single vault. These 'Cities of the Dead' are now considered some of the most significant funerary architecture in North America and draw hundreds of thousands of visitors every year.",
