    "title": "Texas Used to Be Its Own Country (and It Won't Let You Forget)",
    "summary": "The Republic of Texas was an independent nation from 1836 to 1845 with its own president, currency, and navy. It is the only US state that was a fully recognized sovereign country before joining the union.",
    "fullText": "After winning independence from Mexico at the Battle of San Jacinto in 1836, Texas operated as its own sovereign republic for nearly a decade. It had a president (Sam Houston), its own currency (the Texas dollar, which quickly became worthless), a navy, and embassies in London and Paris. The republic was perpetually broke and constantly threatened by Mexican military incursions. Texas finally agreed to annexation by the United States in 1845, which promptly triggered the Mexican-American War. A persistent myth claims that Texas retained the right to split into five separate states upon joining the union, but legal scholars have endlessly debated whether this provision is actually enforceable. What is not debatable is that Texans remain deeply proud of their former nationhood, flying the Lone Star flag at the same height as the American flag, which is technically their right.",
