    "title": "The Longest Street in America Runs Through El Paso",
    "summary": "El Paso's main drag is part of US Route 80, which was once the longest street in the United States at over 2,500 miles. The stretch through downtown El Paso is still one of the most historically layered roads in the country.",
    "fullText": "El Paso sits on the US-Mexico border in a spot where the Rocky Mountains take a break, creating a natural pass that has funneled human traffic for thousands of years. The city's location made it a critical stop on virtually every major east-west route: the Butterfield Overland Mail, the Southern Pacific Railroad, and eventually Route 80, once the southernmost transcontinental highway. El Paso is closer to Los Angeles than it is to Houston, a fact that messes with most people's mental map of Texas. The city is also unique in being essentially one half of an international metropolis, with Ciudad Juarez, Mexico sitting directly across the Rio Grande. Together, the two cities form a metro area of over 2.7 million people. From the air, you can clearly see the border fence cutting between the two downtowns, separated by only a few hundred yards of river.",
