    "title": "The Sixth Floor That Changed American History",
    "summary": "On November 22, 1963, Lee Harvey Oswald fired from the sixth floor of the Texas School Book Depository in Dallas, assassinating President John F. Kennedy. The window he shot from is still there.",
    "fullText": "Dealey Plaza in downtown Dallas is one of the most scrutinized pieces of real estate on Earth. On November 22, 1963, President Kennedy's motorcade passed through the plaza, and shots were fired from the sixth floor of the Texas School Book Depository building overlooking the route. Lee Harvey Oswald was arrested for the murder but was himself shot and killed by nightclub owner Jack Ruby two days later on live national television. The sixth floor is now a museum dedicated to the assassination and its aftermath, with the sniper's perch preserved behind glass exactly as it looked that day. An X painted on Elm Street marks the approximate spot where the fatal shot struck. Despite the Warren Commission's conclusion that Oswald acted alone, polls consistently show that a majority of Americans believe there was a broader conspiracy, making it the most debated crime in the nation's history.",
