    "title": "The USS Lexington Survived More Hits Than Any Carrier in History",
    "summary": "The USS Lexington, now a museum in Corpus Christi, was torpedoed, bombed, and hit by kamikaze pilots so many times during WWII that the Japanese declared it sunk four separate times. It kept coming back.",
    "fullText": "The USS Lexington (CV-16), now permanently moored in Corpus Christi Bay, earned the nickname 'The Blue Ghost' during World War II because the Japanese kept reporting it destroyed, yet it kept reappearing in battle. Tokyo Rose declared it sunk at least four times. The Essex-class aircraft carrier served longer and shot down more enemy planes than any other carrier in US Navy history, participating in virtually every major Pacific campaign from 1943 to 1945. It survived direct hits from torpedoes, bombs, and kamikaze aircraft. After the war, it served as a training carrier until 1991, making it the last WWII-era carrier to be decommissioned. Today, visitors can walk the flight deck, explore the engine room, and even sleep overnight in the crew quarters as part of a scouting program. The ship sits only a few miles from where the first European explorers landed in Texas in 1519.",
