    "summary": "The Frio River in the Hill Country runs so clear you can count pebbles on the bottom in ten feet of water. It has been a beloved swimming and tubing destination for Texans escaping the summer heat for over a century.",
    "fullText": "The Frio River, flowing through the rugged canyons of Real, Uvalde, and Frio Counties in the Texas Hill Country, is widely considered to have the clearest water of any river in the state. Fed by springs emerging from the Edwards Limestone, the river runs cold even in the heat of summer, earning its Spanish name meaning 'cold.' The stretch of river near Leakey and Concan has been a popular swimming and tubing destination for generations of Texans. Garner State Park, on the Frio River, is one of the most visited state parks in Texas. The park features a nightly summer dance on the slab, an outdoor concrete dance floor where families and teenagers two-step under the stars, a tradition dating back to the park's CCC-era origins in the 1930s. The river runs through deep canyons lined with bald cypress, sycamore, and pecan trees, creating a lush riparian corridor in an otherwise semi-arid landscape.",
