    "fullText": "On September 19 and 20, 1863, the Battle of Chickamauga was fought in the forests and fields of northwest Georgia near the Tennessee border. It was the bloodiest two-day battle in the western theater of the Civil War, producing approximately 34,000 combined casualties. Confederate General Braxton Bragg defeated Union General William Rosecrans, who retreated to Chattanooga. The Confederate victory was one of the few in the war's western campaigns but failed to achieve a decisive result, as the Union held Chattanooga and eventually broke out to continue the drive south toward Atlanta. Chickamauga and Chattanooga National Military Park, established in 1890, was the first national military park in the United States. The battlefield preserves open meadows and mature forest where hundreds of monuments and markers identify the positions of the units that fought. The park covers over 9,000 acres across the Georgia-Tennessee border.",
